<HEADLINE>
FT  03 JUL 92 / Foreign Exchanges: Dollar dealt double blow
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EMMA TUCKER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE DOLLAR made a remark-able recovery in late European trading yesterday
after being dealt the double blow of dismal US employment data and a cut in
the Federal Reserve's discount rate, writes Emma Tucker.
The US currency fell nearly two pfennigs to a 16-month low of DM1.4995 on
the news that non-farm payrolls dropped 117,000 in June, confounding market
expectations of a 90,000 rise.
However, a combination of rumours that the Fed was intervening and the fear
of going too short with the currency at such low levels rescued the dollar
from further losses. It ended in London at DM1.5135, after Wednesday's close
of DM1.5170.
Dealers said the dollar's resilience indicated that the bad news had been,
to a certain extent, anticipated. But the dollar later slipped in New York
to a DM1.5075 finish.
The sharp drop in employment was spread broadly across the economy, apart
from a small rise in government employment, and followed a string of poor
economic data last week.
Within an hour of the employment news being released, the Fed announced a
half-point cut in discount rate to 3 per cent, its lowest level since the
summer of 1963.
Most of the big banks followed the Fed governors' unanimous decision to
lower the discount rate by cutting their prime rates  1/2 point to 6 per
cent. Some analysts said they now expected the dollar to head towards its
all-time low of DM1.4460, set in February 1991.
Mr Nicholas Stamenkovic, an economist at DKB International, the Japanese
Bank, said: 'The Fed will probably respond to further weakness with more
rate cuts, so the dollar is likely to go even lower - it could even go into
free fall.'
However, others said they thought the US currency would find support at
DM1.50.
Mr Gerald Holtham, chief international economist at Shearson Lehman, said:
'There is an incredibly strong feeling in the market that the dollar is
fundamentally cheap at these levels, and people do not want to be too short
when the inevitable rally comes.'
With the dollar hogging most of the attention on the foreign exchanges,
there was little scope for action on the EMS currencies. In the morning the
Italian lira came under pressure as rumours of a devaluation swept the
market. One trader said the lack of confidence overseas was increasing.
The currency was also affected by the weakness of the dollar and worries
about the political and economic outlook in Italy. Dealers said the Bank of
Italy had intervened to temper downward pressure on the currency.
The pound had a good day, although it remained at the bottom of the EMS
grid. It edged above DM2.90 to finish at DM2.9025.
</TEXT>
