FT  03 JUL 92 / World Commodities Prices: Danes tighten controls on imported
pigs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By HILARY BARNES
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   COPENHAGEN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
DANISH PIG farmers have set up an extensive system of controls to prevent
any contamination of their herds by imported pigs. The system is a reaction
to the introduction from July 1 of free trade in live animals across borders
between European Community countries.
The Danes are the biggest EC exporters of pigmeat to non-community
countries, especially Japan and the US, which set stringent veterinary
conditions. The US will not permit the import of any Danish pigmeat if it
includes as much a single pig imported to Denmark from other EC countries,
said Mr Bent Sloth, chairman of the Association of Danish Slaughterhouses.
The slaughterhouses' and pig farmers' organisations, in co-operation with
the government and with the authorisation of the European Commission, have
imposed a system by which all imported animals must be ear-marked and no
pigs can be sent to slaughter from any herd containing an imported pig.
Chicago markets were closed yesterday for a pre-Independence Day holiday
