<HEADLINE>
FT  03 JUL 92 / Parliament and Politics: Chancellor firm on DM revaluation
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN and IVOR OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AN OPPOSITION call for the D-Mark to be revalued against other currencies in
the European Exchange Rate Mechanism was last night derided as a U-turn by
chancellor Norman Lamont.
He charged Mr John Smith, his Labour opposite number, with backing away from
his one firm pre-election commitment.
Mr Lamont's attack came after he had endured a difficult time at the hands
of Tory backbenchers concerned that Britain's readiness to accept a
Community-wide minimum rate of value added tax might restrict the
government's future room for manoeuvre.
Sir Peter Tapsell, Conservative MP for Lindsey East, warned that with less
control over indirect taxation on the one hand and exchange and interest
rates on the other, future chancellors could easily find themselves 'boxed
in.'
Mr Smith's call for 'an upward revaluation of the D-Mark' against other ERM
currencies including sterling came in a speech advocating a European
strategy for growth and employment.
The revaluation should be considered in a bid to secure 'co-ordinated
interest rate cuts in every member state,' the probable winner of the
current Labour leadership contest continued. It was worth weighing whether
'the highly unusual circumstances of German unification' did not justify
such a step, he said.
Arguing that Ecofin - the council of economic and finance ministers - should
have 'the determining role' in the shaping of overall economic policy, he
advised against confining the objective of the proposed European central
bank to 'an exclusive concern with price stability.'
Flanked by Mr Michael Portillo, his Treasury lieutenant, Mr Lamont rebuffed
his Tory critics by insisting his preparedness to accept a 15 per cent
minimum EC-wide VAT rate for a limited period would not constrain the
flexibility of the government's tax policy.
Since the domestic minimum was currently 17 1/2 per cent, it was not
'realistic' to expect a cut to below 15 per cent to be implemented in the
next three years, he said. He remained, however, 'highly sceptical' that a
minimum VAT rate was necessary for a single market.
Conserving his attack on Mr Smith's revaluation proposal until the final
moments of his speech, he said that the shadow chancellor had 'told us again
and again' before the election that he did not want to see the pound
devalued.
Opening the debate earlier, Mr Douglas Hurd, the foreign secretary, had said
the government would not make a decision until the autumn on whether MPs
should be asked to proceed with the bill ratifying the Maastricht treaty.
</TEXT>
