FT  03 JUL 92 / Belgian collection exceeds estimate: Saleroom
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SUSAN MOORE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A WELL-TRAVELLED collection of work by the Belgian poet-turned-artist Marcel
Broodthaers caused a sensation at Christie's yesterday.
The nine objects of 1965-66 were all acquired directly from the artist by
the vendor and are witness to Broodthaers' highly developed sense of the
absurd.
Elements of everyday life - mussels and egg shells are particular favourites
 -are combined as puns or ironic comments on the economic and political life
of the period.
Lot after lot soared way over its estimate, realising a total of Pounds
1.28m. 'Armoire Blanche et Table Blanche', which presents a kitchen table
covered in egg shells and the cabinet above packed full of them, achieved
the top price of Pounds 396,000, paid by dealers Berggruen &amp; Zevi on behalf
of a private client. It was estimated at Pounds 80,000-120,000.
The company also secured a 'Panneau de Moules' for Pounds 88,000, while a
punning moule casserole fetched Pounds 176,000 (estimate Pounds
15,000-Pounds 20,000). Various bidders had hoped to secure the entire
collection to keep it intact.
British contemporary art fared less well during the day. Lucien Freud's
painting of a naked girl asleep was bought in at Sotheby's at Pounds
300,000. In the afternoon at Christie's, his portrait of a man in a sports
shirt tipped the bottom estimate, realising Pounds 275,000. His 'Woman in
Profile' also failed to reach the reserve.
The sale's star lot, a small Francis Bacon portrait, did sell - but
substantially below target. London dealer Thomas Gibson bought it for Pounds
110,000. It was Bacon's last portrait of Isabel Rawsthorne, a favourite
model who had also sat for the likes of Picasso, Epstein and Giacometti.
Sotheby's top price of Pounds 319,000 came from Lucio Fontana's pierced
egg-shape 'La Fine di Dio'.
</TEXT>
