<HEADLINE>
FT  03 JUL 92 / Retail pay deals halved in value
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AVERAGE PAY settlements in retailing and distribution have more than halved
in value in the past year and are below the average for the whole economy,
according to a report.
Industrial Relations Services, the independent pay and conditions group,
found in a survey of 100 pay reviews in the four months to April that the
median was 4.2 per cent against 8.5 per cent for the corresponding period
last year and 4.4 per cent for the whole economy this year.
Thirteen of the 100 organisations had implemented pay freezes or deferrals
of up to 12 months.
However, where general freezes are in operation, it has been common for
low-paid employees to receive an award as companies comply with
wages-council orders.
The report identifies a trend by companies to stretch pay budgets through
profit-related pay.
For example, Robert Dyas, the ironmonger, has a six-month pay pause in
operation to be reviewed at the end of September.
However, the company has also introduced a profit-related pay scheme which
it says will give some 80 per cent of its 570 retail and management
employees net increases in pay of between 5 per cent and 6 per cent - with
no additional costs incurred on the paybill.
Bulletin 307, Industrial Relations Services, 18-20 Highbury Place, London N5
1QP. By subscription.
</TEXT>
