<HEADLINE>
FT  03 JUL 92 / Hotel bookings at a low
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GUY DE JONQUIERES, Consumer Industries Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
OCCUPANCY rates at English hotels were lower in the first four months of
this year than in the same period of any year since 1980, according to a
survey by the English Tourist Board and Horwath Consulting, the leisure
consultants.
They found average monthly occupancy rates were as much as 9 percentage
points below those of the same period last year, when the Gulf war severely
depressed tourism.
The survey found that London occupancy rates improved slightly in April to
62 per cent from 59 per cent a year before. In England as a whole occupancy
was only 45 per cent - 4 percentage points lower than a year before.
Mr Geoff Parkinson, a Horwath director, said the decline in the industry
began in September 1990, four months before the Gulf war, and had been
caused mainly by the recession. Hotels in all price ranges were suffering,
and many were trading at a loss.
Horwath-ETB English Hotel Occupancy Study. Horwath Consulting, 8 Baker
Street, London W1M 1DA. Tel: 071-486-5191.
</TEXT>
