FT  03 JUL 92 / Japan urges US to keep forces in Pacific
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NANCY DUNNE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE US must maintain armed forces in the Pacific as a 'stabilising factor'
for the peace and prosperity of the region, Japanese prime minister Kiichi
Miyazawa said on his first state visit to Washington.
In a speech yesterday, Mr Miyazawa sought to shift the spotlight from
contentious trade issues to US-Japanese economic and political partnership
in the region.
He said the most pressing regional concern was a reduction of tension on the
Korean peninsula, where a North-South dialogue for reconciliation must be
supported by China and Russia as well.
Mr Miyazawa hoped to settle his differences with Russia over Japan's former
Northern islands with Russian President Boris Yeltsin.
'I can easily imagine how the Russian people, who have long been taught that
these islands are Soviet territory, may face a strong psychological block in
coming to terms with the return of these islands to Japan,' he said.
'However, for our two countries to act as if the problem did not exist would
only complicate the matter further.'
