<HEADLINE>
FT  03 JUL 92 / World Trade News: Nafta deal hangs over summit
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAMIAN FRASER and NANCY DUNNE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MEXICO CITY, WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
PRESIDENT George Bush will meet Mexico's Carlos Salinas in San Diego,
California, on July 14, as the two countries - along with Canada - head into
the final stage of negotiations on a North American Free Trade Agreement
(Nafta).
But Mr Bush yesterday dismissed speculation that a Nafta deal would be
concluded during Mr Salinas' quick visit. 'It is not a scheduled event,' Mr
Bush said.
Mr Salinas said in an interview that 'in the next weeks (the treaty) should
finish and be initialled'.
According to US law, the treaty can only be signed by Mr Bush 90 days after
he has notified Congress of this intention. Mr Salinas said that at the
moment the plan was to sign the treaty and present the agreement to the US
Congress before the November elections.
But the Mexican government has consistently underestimated the time it would
take to complete negotiations.
Rumours persist that the free trade agreement will not be initialled until
October.
Kidnapping dispute, Page 4
</TEXT>
