<HEADLINE>
FT  03 JUL 92 / French lorry blockade worsens
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALICE RAWSTHORN and BETHAN HUTTON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS, LONDON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE French government yesterday stepped up its efforts to end the lorry
drivers' dispute as many main roads remained blocked, causing shortages of
food, fuel and medical supplies across the country.
Mr Pierre Beregovoy, prime minister, warned the truckers, who are protesting
against new rules to curb dangerous driving, that their licences would be
suspended unless the road blocks were removed.
Peugeot, the car company, blamed the dispute for its decision temporarily to
lay off 12,000 workers at a factory in Sochaux-Montbeliard, because of a
parts shortage.
In Britain, Peugeot Talbot, its UK subsidiary, said it had been forced to
cancel a day's production at its two assembly plants near Coventry because
of serious disruption in the supply of parts from France.
Some 2,000 workers on last night's and today's shifts were told to stay at
home on full pay. The company said production was expected to resume on
Monday.
In France, petrol rationing started at some filling stations in Paris,
Toulouse, Saint-Etienne and Lyons. Hundreds of tourists were trapped at
Channel ports and the borders with Spain, Italy, and Germany.
Seven police and one protester were injured when police charged a
demonstration by truckers and other workers at Cherbourg.
The government is today launching a special committee of inquiry into the
new rules, whereby French motorists are awarded six points on their licences
and lose points if they commit driving offences. Any driver losing all six
points automatically forfeits his licence. The truckers say they should be
allocated extra points because, as professional drivers, they spend longer
on the road.
Mr Beregovoy said the lorry drivers could make their case to the committee,
providing the protest stopped. 'We cannot negotiate while millions of
tourists and millions of French people are being held hostage,' he said.
However, the government yesterday made a concession by saying that the
information on speed and driving time contained in the 'black boxes'
installed in their cabs would not be used as evidence for driving offences.
The authorities had limited success in persuading the lorry drivers to
remove road blocks. A barricade of 800 lorries on the A6 motorway south of
Paris dispersed during the morning, and roads in Brittany were clear by
lunchtime.
But the truckers stepped up the dispute in other areas by concentrating on
specific targets such as petrol depots. Two of the biggest depots in the
Paris region, at Val d'Oise and Gennevilliers, were sealed off by lorries.
Britain's Freight Transport Association described it as the 'worst blockade
ever experienced', and said it was 'concerned that drivers are being lured
into blockades by the action of motorway toll attendants, or through lack of
adequate information in English'.
'There are reports of French nationals tampering with vehicles, turning off
refrigeration motors,' said Mr John Hix, of the FTA's international
department. 'My advice to drivers who are stuck is to keep calm.'
British holidaymakers were yesterday still being advised to keep away from
French motorways, but Europ Assistance, the emergency recovery organisation,
warned drivers to check their holiday insurance before cancelling a holiday
outright. Around 50 per cent of insurance companies would not pay out for
holidays cancelled only because of the threat of delays, it said.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 2
