<HEADLINE>
FT  03 JUL 92 / US discount rate cut after sharp rise in jobless
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL PROWSE and PETER NORMAN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON, LONDON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE US Federal Reserve responded swiftly to fresh signs of economic weakness
yesterday by cutting the discount rate by half a percentage point to 3 per
cent, the lowest level since 1963.
The move came shortly after the Commerce Department reported an unexpectedly
sharp rise in the unemployment rate last month - from 7.5 per cent to 7.8
per cent, the highest level since 1984. The rise in the jobless rate could
be a severe political embarrassment for President George Bush, who welcomed
the Fed's move but conceded that the recovery was not as robust as he had
hoped.
The Fed also signalled a half-point cut from 3.75 per cent to 3.25 per cent
in the overnight federal funds rate, the rate at which banks lend to each
other. Leading commercial banks reacted by cutting their prime lending rates
from 6.5 per cent to 6 per cent, the lowest level in nearly two decades. The
prime rate influences the cost of a wide range of consumer and business
loans.
Bond prices surged on Wall Street. By early afternoon the 30-year long bond
was up by 1 13/32 points, pushing the yield down to 7.626 per cent. The Dow
Jones Industrial Average, after rising sharply in previous days, retreated
23.81 to 3,330.29, reflecting dismay at the poor employment figures.
The employment news initially pushed the dollar down by 2 pfennigs to a
16-month low of DM1.4995. It later recovered in European trading to close in
London at DM1.5135 before slipping back in New York to DM1.5075.
The Fed move followed intense lobbying by the White House, with both Mr Bush
and Mr Nicholas Brady, the treasury secretary, making public calls for lower
interest rates.
The timing of the rate cut - just ahead of next week's Group of Seven
economic summit in Munich - was particularly convenient for the Bush
administration, which intends to stress the importance of co-ordinated
measures to stimulate global growth.
The Fed move was part of a 'major commitment on the part of industrial
countries towards growth', a senior US Treasury official said yesterday.
The three biggest G7 nations have now signalled steps which they believe
will promote non-inflationary growth in the world economy in the medium
term.
On Wednesday, the Bonn government announced a tough 1993 budget and
four-year savings plan that is supposed to pave the way for lower German
interest rates.
Although the Bundesbank yesterday left its key interest rates unchanged, the
German economy is due to receive a short-term DM12bn (Pounds 4.1bn) boost
from the discontinuation this week of a special 7.5 per cent income tax
surcharge levied for the past year to help finance the absorption of the new
states of the former East Germany.
In Japan, the ruling Liberal Democratic party has proposed a wide range of
pump-priming measures, including a large-scale supplementary budget that
would probably be introduced in September. LDP officials have suggested the
package could be worth between Y6,000bn and Y10,000bn (Pounds 25bn-Pounds
42bn).
Taken together, these moves represented a 'very substantial change' in the
policymaking climate, the US Treasury official said. World leaders, he
indicated, had begun to recognise that the main challenge was sustaining
growth rather than fighting inflation.
The Fed, however, justified the discount rate cut in purely domestic terms.
It followed 'sustained weakness in credit and money growth, continued
movement toward price stability and the uneven progress of the economic
recovery'.
The seven Fed governors voted unanimously for the cut, the first since
December and the seventh since the recession began nearly two years ago.
The employment numbers were bad enough to draw the sting from charges that
Mr Alan Greenspan, the Fed chairman, bowed to political pressure for lower
interest rates. Financial markets had expected no change in the unemployment
rate and a rise in non-farm employment.
The actual figures were much worse. After months of gradual improvement,
employment fell by 117,000, with sizeable falls in manufacturing,
construction and the service sector. The unemployment rate - politically the
most sensitive number - jumped to 7.8 per cent.
The employment figures followed other poor economic indicators pointing to a
slowdown in growth in recent months. Most forecasters believe the economy is
still growing sluggishly but at a slower pace than the 2.7 per cent annual
rate recorded in the first quarter.
