<HEADLINE>
FT  03 JUL 92 / PM scorns Thatcher views on Europe
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS, Political Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR JOHN MAJOR dismissed Lady Thatcher's views on Europe last night as those
of 'little England' after she used her maiden speech in the House of Lords
to launch another attack on the Maastricht treaty.
His harsh words came in a speech designed to rally Tory MPs behind the
government on Europe and the economy.
The prime minister admitted that he shared their concerns about the sluggish
pace of economic recovery. But he said the government had secured the
prospect of an 'end to inflation' during the present parliament.
Mr Major, who had earlier faced a direct attack from Lady Thatcher over his
determination to press on with ratification of Maastricht, said he would
keep Britain at the centre of decision-making in the Community. In what was
taken as a sharp rebuff to his predecessor, he said: 'I do not want us to be
little England, impoverished, sour in isolation, bereft of hope, languishing
on the sidelines of Europe, on the sidelines of history.'
