<HEADLINE>
FT  03 JUL 92 / Commodities and Agriculture: Nervous platinum market climbs
to 13-month high
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KENNETH GOODING, Mining Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE PLATINUM price yesterday continued the rise prompted by renewed
political tension in South Africa, which accounts for about 70 per cent of
world production. Platinum's performance and an unexpected cut in the US
discount rate helped push gold through an important technical resistance
point, Dollars 345 a troy ounce.
Since Monday, fears about possible strikes at the South African mines have
lifted platinum in London by Dollars 20.65 an ounce or nearly 6 per cent.
Yesterday the metal closed in London up another Dollars 3.90 an ounce at
Dollars 387.90, its highest level since May last year. On the New York
Commodity Exchange (Nymex) July platinum reached Dollars 400 an ounce
yesterday morning.
Analysts suggested a South African miners' strike was unlikely but it was
too risky to go short of platinum during the present rally. Platinum in the
past has moved up Dollars 50 to Dollars 100 an ounce in a matter of weeks,
they pointed out.
Mr Jeremy Coombes, analyst at Johnson Matthey, the world's largest platinum
marketing organisation, said that platinum might move to Dollars 400 an
ounce more quickly than he previously expected and a sustained move above
Dollars 400 could trigger renewed interest by US investors. However, Mr Andy
Smith, analyst at Union Bank of Switzerland, suggested the market was not
taking account of weakening Japanese economic activity.
