FT  03 JUL 92 / Chief executive sought for port
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRIS TIGHE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   THE Whitehaven Development Company
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
the latest initiative aimed at tackling the Cumbrian port's economic
structural problems - is looking for a Pounds 40,000-a-year chief executive
to steer the town towards a future based on the service sector.
The company was created in response to Whitehaven's worsening unemployment
and its difficulties in attracting inward industrial investment.
The company's priorities include fostering leisure uses for Whitehaven's
port, which has just lost its last commercial cargo with the ending of
phosphate rock imports for the town's Albright &amp; Wilson chemicals works.
Coal shipping trade ceased in the 1980s when the last pits in west Cumbria
closed. The development company, a joint venture with the West Cumbria
Development Agency, hopes to smarten up the town and attract tourists.
Unemployment in Whitehaven is 8.6 per cent, below the national average, but
the area is being hit by the shedding of 5,000 construction jobs at the
nearby Sellafield nuclear waste reprocessing plant. Cumbria County Council
has forecast unemployment rates of up to 25 per cent in the borough of
Copeland, which includes Whitehaven.
Mr David Shelton, development company board member, said promotion of
leisure and tourism would run alongside development of a business park and
industrial estate. But he warned: 'To think we will attract new heavy
industry opportunities would be deluding ourselves.'
