FT  03 JUL 92 / Health service complaints rise 19%
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN PIKE, Social Affairs Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
COMPLAINTS to the health service commissioner last year were the highest
since the establishment of the health ombudsman system in 1973.
Mr William Reid, the commissioner, received 1,176 complaints - a rise of
nearly 19 per cent on the previous year. 'The similar experience of other
ombudsmen suggests that the increase owes much to growing public awareness
of how to complain and to whom,' Mr Reid says in his annual report.
He stresses that it is vital that patients, faced with 'an array of new
authorities and organisational arrangements' under the National Health
Service reforms, should know how to make their complaints.
He had been assured by the government that all dissatisfied NHS patients
would have access to the ombudsman system.
Health Service Commissioner, Annual Report for 1991-92. HMSO, Pounds 10.30.
