<HEADLINE>
FT  03 JUL 92 / They play it again as time goes by
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GARY MEAD, Marketing Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   A MOVIE that demonstrates how entertaining a bad movie can be
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
that is how American critic Ms Pauline Kael described Casablanca, and for
six days from today London cinema-goers will have the chance to judge for
themselves.
The black-and-white classic is to be screened at the Empire cinema in
Leicester Square, and Turner Entertainment, which bought the MGM film
library in 1986, has gone into marketing and public relations overdrive to
promote one of its most famous assets.
In the UK, United International Pictures has the marketing rights for
Casablanca - and certainly one of the best marketing moves is to try to
convince the public that they are being offered some kind of exclusively
special deal.
Thus between today and July 8 only some 35,000 people - four daily shows
plus late nighters today and tomorrow in the 1,300-capacity cinema - will be
able to see Casablanca at the Empire, paying either Pounds 6.50 or Pounds 8
a seat.
Turner is unwilling to say how much it has spent on marketing Casablanca -
'we don't discuss financial figures' - but United is running a thorough
advertising campaign on the London Underground. That is just the tip of the
iceberg - the public relations promotion of the film has been massive, with
a glossy 24-page pack of everything you could possibly want to know about
the movie, media interviews and other hype.
If, after all that, you still don't make it to the Empire - where ticket
staff say 'there are still plenty of seats available' - then you could
always pop along to the National Film Theatre and spend Pounds 10.99 on a
video version.
