<HEADLINE>
FT  03 JUL 92 / Maxwell report to be kept secret
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE Securities and Investments Board, the City's chief watchdog, said
yesterday that it would not publish the text of a long-awaited report on
regulators' responsibilities in the Maxwell affair.
'SIB has been advised that publication of the full report could prejudice
pending legal proceedings,' the watchdog said in a statement yesterday.
Instead, it would eventually publish a statement setting out its assessments
of regulators' roles and outlining actions it is taking.
It will also publish conclusions of a report by the Investment Management
Regulatory Organisation, the self-regulating body for the fund management
industry, about its own role in the Maxwell affair.
Imro authorised and supervised two Maxwell-controlled companies which
managed nearly Pounds 800m of pension funds. Fund managers lent securities
from pension funds and those securities were later used as collateral for
loans to Robert Maxwell's personal interests.
Imro's report is believed to accept some of the blame for failing to spot
the theft of more than Pounds 400m from pension funds controlled by Robert
Maxwell, and to be critical of some of his professional advisers including
the auditors Coopers &amp; Lybrand.
Coopers is said to have protested vigorously to SIB about Imro's
characterisation of its role.
