<TEXT>
MONGOLIA'S ex-communist ruling party crushed its democratic opponents to win
70 out of 76 parliamentary seats in last Sunday's election, according to
official results released yesterday, Reuter reports from Ulan Bator.
The General Election Commission said the Mongolian People's Revolutionary
Party (MPRP) polled 56.9 per cent of the total vote, six percentage points
down from its showing in Mongolia's first free elections in 1990.
The Democratic Coalition won the second highest number of votes with about
17 per cent. It won four seats in the country's new single-chamber
parliament. The Social Democratic Party came in third with 10 per cent of
the vote, securing one seat. The final seat will go to an MPRP member who
ran as an independent.
The democratic parties have yet to decide whether they will go through with
a threat to boycott the parliament.
