FT  02 JUL 92 / International Company News: Citicorp in Dollars 175m
disposal of assets
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN FRIEDMAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CITICORP, the leading US bank that is seeking to bolster its capital base,
said last night it had raised Dollars 175m by means of the sale of assets
related to its merchant processing unit for credit cards.
The asset disposal, part of the bank's efforts to lift its main Tier 1
capital ratio from its present level of 4.06 per cent to the range of
between 5 and 5 1/2 per cent, is the latest in a string of fund-raising
security issues and sales of assets defined as non-strategic.
Citicorp said that since the beginning of 1991 - when Mr John Reed, the
chairman, first announced a plan for strengthening the company's capital
position and restoring profitability by the end of 1992 - it had raised the
equivalent of about Dollars 2.8bn in Tier 1 capital.
The total amount of capital at the end of March 1992 was Dollars 9.1bn.
Citicorp's target is capital of Dollars 12bn to Dollars 13bn.
Yesterday's disposal of certain assets in Citicorp's credit card processing
business does not mark a withdrawal from the sector. Citicorp emphasised it
would continue to focus on providing credit card services to consumers, who
presently hold 41m Citicorp-issued cards.
The business affected by the sale, which is known as Citicorp Establishment
Services, processes an annual sales volume of about Dollars 30bn in the US
and provides authorisation, processing and settlement to merchants who
accept credit cards.
The buyers of the assets are Welsh, Carson, Anderson &amp; Stowe, Prudential
Equity Investors and William Blair &amp; co.
</TEXT>
