<HEADLINE>
FT  02 JUL 92 / International Company News: South Africa to change control
of airports
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DANIEL GREEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SOUTH AFRICA is to take its airports and air traffic services out of direct
government control and into two new companies.
Mr Piet Welgemoed, South African transport minister, will today announce the
approval of proposals for the commercialisation of nine airports and air
traffic and navigation services, said Price Waterhouse, the London
accountancy firm which helped draw up the proposals.
The South African government will remain the sole shareholder in the
companies but both will be run on a commercial basis and the government
should be able to phase out subsidies.
The biggest of the airports, Jan Smuts at Johannesburg, handles 12m
passengers a year, comparable with Geneva airport. Eight others will be
affected, including Cape Town and Durban airports.
South Africa is increasingly popular for air traffic: over the past year, 25
more airlines have applied for access rights.
Legislation will have to be passed before the plan can proceed and this is
expected by next spring. The government will set up a regulation committee
for the two companies, but it will not be able to intervene in everyday
affairs.
</TEXT>
