<HEADLINE>
FT  02 JUL 92 / GEC increases profits by 1% to Pounds 829m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHARLES LEADBEATER, Industrial Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CANCELLATION of the European Fighter Aircraft (EFA) could have serious
consequences for the General Electric Company's radar factories in
Edinburgh, Lord Weinstock, managing director, warned yesterday after
announcing a 1 per cent increase in pre-tax profits to Pounds 829m last
year.
He said the company had not calculated how many jobs would be at risk, but
GEC is planning to develop the EFA's radar on the basis that Germany may
pull out of the project's production phase.
Lord Weinstock was confident that Britain's other EFA partners - Italy and
Spain - would develop a fighter regardless of the German decision.
He said GEC's results vindicated its strategy of expansion in Europe through
joint ventures with Alsthom of France (power engineering) and Siemens of
Germany (telecommunications). GEC also has a joint venture with General
Electric of the US in consumer appliances.
Profits from continental Europe rose 32 per cent to Pounds 199m, offsetting
a fall in UK profits from Pounds 428m to Pounds 393m.
Operating profit rose 2 per cent to Pounds 702m for the year to March 31, on
a Pounds 27m fall in turnover to Pounds 9.44bn, largely due to a strong
performance from GEC-Alsthom. Improved profits from GEC's 50 per cent share
in that venture helped profits in the power systems division rise 27 per
cent to Pounds 157m.
Operating profit at GPT, the telecommunications joint venture with Siemens,
rose Pounds 2m to Pounds 127m on a 10 per cent fall in turnover to Pounds
1.1bn. Better financial discipline at GPT also helped GEC's cash reserves
rise sharply, from Pounds 528m to Pounds 876m. GEC has net cash of about
Pounds 1.46bn.
The consumer goods joint venture with GE raised operating profits by Pounds
3m to Pounds 21m. Turnover fell Pounds 3m to Pounds 268m. Profits at
electronic systems, which mainly comprises Marconi, the defence electronics
subsidiary, fell Pounds 9m to Pounds 260m. The Picker medical equipment
business improved profits by Pounds 6m to Pounds 32m, but profits at the
office equipment and printing division fell by Pounds 9m to Pounds 17m.
The board is recommending a 5.2 per cent increase in the final dividend to
7.05p for a total of 9.6p (up from 9.25p). Earnings per share were unchanged
at 18.6p.
Lex, Page 22; Details, Page 25; Market report, Page 48
